<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<databaseChangeLog xmlns="http://www.liquibase.org/xml/ns/dbchangelog"
                   xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
                   xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.liquibase.org/xml/ns/dbchangelog
                   http://www.liquibase.org/xml/ns/dbchangelog/dbchangelog-4.20.xsd">

    <!--
      Backfill RBAC rows for deployments that existed before @PreAuthorize was enforced. Without this, every
      pre-existing workspace and project would have no administrators and nobody could access anything once the
      permission checks turn on.

      Strategy: promote every workspace_user that is still on the column default (EDITOR=1) to workspace ADMIN, then
      seed one project_user ADMIN row per (workspace_user × project-in-that-workspace) pair that does not already have
      one. Both statements run in a single changeset so the database commit is atomic — partial application would
      leave the deployment half-RBAC'd and is harder to recover from than re-running the whole thing.

      Safety:
       - <preConditions> is the primary re-run guard: on a populated database the changeset is marked RAN exactly
         once, so a normal re-run is a no-op regardless of the WHERE clauses below. The WHERE/NOT EXISTS clauses are
         defensive — they only matter on the abnormal path where an operator has run `clearCheckSums` and forced
         re-application. In that case `workspace_role = 1` filters keep already-promoted admins from being re-touched
         (their ordinal is now 0) and `WHERE NOT EXISTS` prevents duplicate project_user rows. A demoted-to-EDITOR
         admin would still be re-promoted on a clearCheckSums re-run; operators relying on that path must be aware.
       - <rollback> is documented as no-op because there is no way to recover the original distinct workspace_role
         values once the blanket promote has run; rolling back would silently drop assigned admin grants.

      Auditability: the blanket-promote semantics are potentially surprising (every default-EDITOR user becomes
      ADMIN), so the companion changeset below seeds a one-row `rbac_backfill_report` audit record with the
      pre-backfill counts. Operators can SELECT from it after deployment to verify the migration's blast radius
      matches expectations. The report table is created before the backfill runs and populated after, so the counts
      recorded are the deltas the backfill actually applied.
    -->

    <changeSet id="202604061200050-audit-report-table" author="Ivica Cardic">
        <!--
          Create the audit report table BEFORE the backfill runs so the INSERT in the next changeset has somewhere
          to write. Kept in a separate changeset (instead of CREATE TABLE + backfill in one) because the backfill
          changeset uses runInTransaction="true" and some Liquibase DDL executors prefer DDL to live in its own
          atomic unit for rollback granularity. The table is auto-skipped on re-run by Liquibase checksum tracking.
        -->
        <createTable tableName="rbac_backfill_report">
            <column name="id" type="BIGINT" autoIncrement="true">
                <constraints primaryKey="true" nullable="false"/>
            </column>
            <column name="executed_at" type="TIMESTAMP" defaultValueComputed="CURRENT_TIMESTAMP">
                <constraints nullable="false"/>
            </column>
            <column name="workspace_users_promoted" type="BIGINT">
                <constraints nullable="false"/>
            </column>
            <column name="project_users_seeded" type="BIGINT">
                <constraints nullable="false"/>
            </column>
            <column name="notes" type="VARCHAR(500)"/>
        </createTable>
    </changeSet>

    <changeSet id="202604061200050-backfill-project-user" author="Ivica Cardic" runInTransaction="true">
        <preConditions onError="HALT" onFail="MARK_RAN">
            <!--
              Skip the changeset on fresh installs (empty workspace_user). We cannot use `<sqlCheck
              expectedResult="true">SELECT EXISTS(...)</sqlCheck>` here because PostgreSQL returns the boolean as 't'
              or 'f', not the literal 'true' / 'false' — that mismatch would silently mark the changeset as RAN on
              populated databases and lock out every existing EE user. `<not><rowCount expectedRows="0"/></not>`
              works across dialects because `rowCount` compares integers, not booleans.

              onError="HALT" / onFail="MARK_RAN" are split deliberately: a precondition-check error (permission
              denied on workspace_user, missing table, connection failure) must HALT the deployment so operators
              see the problem at startup. Folding errors into MARK_RAN would silently boot a half-RBAC'd database
              where the backfill never ran but the change is marked complete. Only a FAIL (the populated-db check
              legitimately returned "empty") may safely MARK_RAN.
            -->
            <not>
                <rowCount tableName="workspace_user" expectedRows="0"/>
            </not>
        </preConditions>

        <comment>
            Atomic RBAC backfill: promote default-EDITOR workspace_user rows to ADMIN (ordinal 0), seed
            project_user ADMIN rows for every (workspace member, project) pair lacking one, then record the row
            counts for operator audit. The promote/seed/audit steps run as a single CTE-based statement so the
            audit row reflects exactly the deltas this run applied (CTEs use RETURNING to count actual mutations,
            avoiding the double-count that a SELECT-from-the-post-state query would produce on a clearCheckSums
            re-run where prior runs already left admin rows behind).
        </comment>

        <sql>
            WITH promoted AS (
                UPDATE workspace_user SET workspace_role = 0 WHERE workspace_role = 1
                RETURNING 1
            ),
            seeded AS (
                INSERT INTO project_user (
                    project_id, user_id, project_role, created_date, created_by,
                    last_modified_date, last_modified_by, version
                )
                SELECT p.id, wu.user_id, 0, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'rbac-backfill',
                       CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 'rbac-backfill', 0
                FROM project p
                JOIN workspace_user wu ON wu.workspace_id = p.workspace_id
                WHERE NOT EXISTS (
                    SELECT 1 FROM project_user pu
                    WHERE pu.project_id = p.id AND pu.user_id = wu.user_id
                )
                RETURNING 1
            )
            INSERT INTO rbac_backfill_report (workspace_users_promoted, project_users_seeded, notes)
            SELECT
                (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM promoted),
                (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM seeded),
                'RBAC backfill run. workspace_users_promoted = rows updated from EDITOR to ADMIN by this run. '
                || 'project_users_seeded = creator-inferred ADMIN rows inserted by this run. Counts are deltas, '
                || 'not totals \u2014 sum across all rbac_backfill_report rows for the cumulative blast radius.'
        </sql>

        <rollback>
            <!--
              Rollback is intentionally a hard failure because the forward migration's promote half is irreversible:
              we cannot reconstruct the original distinct workspace_role values (everything was ordinal 1 before,
              but admins promoted some rows to other ordinals between the migration and the rollback). Even so,
              we tag the backfill-inserted project_user rows with created_by='rbac-backfill' specifically so that a
              dev-mode operator performing manual recovery can DELETE them without risk of sweeping legitimate
              application-inserted 'system' rows. A silent no-op rollback (the prior implementation) would let an
              operator believe a rollback succeeded while the schema and data were unchanged \u2014 worse, on dev
              environments rolling forward again would attempt to redo the backfill on top of the post-rollback
              state. Failing loudly forces operators to consciously acknowledge the irreversibility and either
              perform manual recovery or accept the data loss.
            -->
            <sql>
                DO $$
                BEGIN
                    RAISE EXCEPTION 'BACKFILL_ROLLBACK_BLOCKED: changeset 202604061200050-backfill-project-user '
                        'cannot be safely rolled back. The forward migration promoted EDITOR rows to ADMIN and '
                        'seeded creator-inferred admin grants; reversing it would silently drop legitimate admin '
                        'assignments. To force-rollback in dev: manually restore workspace_user.workspace_role, '
                        'then DELETE FROM project_user WHERE created_by = ''rbac-backfill'' (safe \u2014 the '
                        'sentinel scopes the delete to rows this migration inserted and avoids collisions with '
                        'application-inserted ''system'' rows), then mark the changeset rolled back via Liquibase '
                        'tooling.';
                END $$;
            </sql>
        </rollback>
    </changeSet>
</databaseChangeLog>
